statement:
Suppose the motion of a spring-mass system is described by the following
differential equation

\begin{align*}2u'' + 2\gamma u' + 18u = 0, \quad u(0) = 1, \quad u'(0) = -\frac{11}2\end{align*}

\textbf{(c)} Find the general solution of

\begin{align*}t^2y'' - 4ty' + 6y = 3t, \quad (t > 0)\end{align*}

provided that \emph{y\textsubscript{1}(t) = t\textsuperscript{2}} and
\emph{y\textsubscript{2}(t) = t\textsuperscript{3}} are two linearly
independent solutions of the homogeneous equation

\begin{align*}\displaystyle
t^2y'' - 4ty' + 6y = 0\end{align*}

sols:
We are given the solution to the homogeneous equation. To find the
solution with the nonzero right-hand side, we will try variation of
parameters.

Given $t^2$ and $t^3$ satisfy the homogeneous ODE, we will make an
ansatz

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}y = f(t) t^2 + g(t) t^3\end{align*}

where f(t) and g(t) are unknown functions. If we differentiate this we
get

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}y' = f'(t) t^2 + 2 f(t) t + g'(t) t^3 + 3 g(t) t^2\end{align*}

and to avoid having more than a single derivative upon f and g in
computing $y''$, we will set

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}f'(t) t^2 + g'(t) t^3 = 0\end{align*}

so that

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}y' = 2 f(t) t + 3 g(t) t^2.\end{align*}

Notice that by making the assumption, the original first derivative
remains unchanged. It is important that we make this step, otherwise
when we try to solve the ODE we will have one equation for two unknowns.
This assumption adds extra information that allows us to solve the
problem. Differentiating again, we get

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}y'' = 2 f'(t) t + 2 f(t) + 3 g'(t) t^2 + 6 g(t) t.\end{align*}

Now we take our derivatives and substitute them into the original
equation:

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}t^2 (2 f'(t) t + 2 f(t) + 3 g'(t) t^2 + 6 g(t) t) - 4t (2 f(t) t + 3 g(t) t^2) + 6 (f(t) t^2 + g(t) t^3) =3t.\end{align*}

After expanding and simplifying, we get

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}2 t^3 f'(t) + 3 t^4 g'(t) = 3t.\end{align*}

Now we have two first-order ODEs for f and g:

\begin{align*}
t^2 f' + t^3 g' &= 0 \\ 
2t^3 f' + 3t^4 g' &= 3t.\end{align*}

The first equation implies

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}f' = -t g'\end{align*}

which can be substituted into the second equation:

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}-2t^4 g' + 3t^4 g' &= 3t\\
t^4 g' &= 3t\\
g' &= \frac{3}{t^3}\\
g &= \frac{-3}{2 t^2} + C_1.\end{align*}

Also, from above,

\begin{align*}
f' &= -t g' = \frac{-3}{t^2}\\
f &= \frac{3}{t} + C_2.\end{align*}

Having solve for f(t) and g(t) we get that the general solution to our
problem is

\begin{align*}y = f(t) t^2 + g(t) t^3 = C_1 t^3 + C_2 t^2 + \frac{3}{2} t.\end{align*}
